This set of parameters is used by the gNB to configure the UE in DRX mode, allowing UE to have enough time to receive SIB1 from the unknown neighbor cell and report its CGI to the gNB. It is recommended to carefully configure these parameters because too short time in UE in DRX mode may result to insufficient time to receive CGI report, but too long UE idle time may affect performance.
This parameter indicates the usability purpose of Special DRX profile used for NR ANR functionality solution
Range and step: any (0), intraNR (1), intraNRFR2 (2), intraNRSA (3), intraNRSAintraFreq (4), intraNRSAinterFreq (5), intraNRNSA (6), intraNRNSAintraFreq (7), intraNRNSAinterFreq (8), interRATeUTRA (9)

Parameter name: New Radio Discontinuous Reception Transmission distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated NRDRX instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRDRX-2  NRDRX-2

Parameter name: DRX scheduling weight for DL enabled
Description: This parameter enables/disables the DRX DL scheduling weight for connected DRX user DL scheduling.

Parameter name: DRX scheduling weight for UL enabled
Description: This parameter enables/disables the DRX UL scheduling weight for connected DRX user UL scheduling.
This structure gathers the parameters to configure the micro DTX optimized scheduler.

Parameter name: Micro-DTX optimized scheduler support enabled for UEs in CA
Description: This parameter enables/disables micro-DTX optimized scheduler for UEs in CA.    This parameter is ignored if NRCELL.actEnhDtxOptimizedScheduler is set to FALSE.

Parameter name: DRB differentiation enabled in micro-DTX optimized scheduler
Description: This parameter enables/disables DRB differentiation in micro-DTX optimized scheduler. Delay parameters depend on traffic type.    This parameter is ignored if NRCELL.actEnhDtxOptimizedScheduler is set to FALSE.

Parameter name: Micro-DTX optimized scheduler enhancements enabled for UEs with DRX
Description: This parameter enables/disables micro-DTX optimized scheduler enhancements for UEs with DRX.    This parameter is ignored if NRCELL.actEnhDtxOptimizedScheduler is set to FALSE.

Parameter name: Delay threshold since last scheduling for micro DTX optimized scheduler
Description: Whenever a UE could be put under DTX optimized scheduling and provided that the value of this parameter is greater than 0, the scheduler shall first check if the delay since the last scheduling of this UE, which emptied its associated buffers, is greater than or equal to the value of this parameter.    If the measured delay is greater than or equal to the value of this parameter, the UE is not eligible to DTX optimized scheduling. Thus, no retention delay will be applied to schedule the UE non-GBR (except 5QI5) DRB traffic.    Whenever this parameter is equal to 0, this check is bypassed.

Parameter name: Maximum retention delay for micro DTX optimized scheduler
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum duration in ms between the first received data (possibly gathering several packets received at a similar time) in a bundle and the last one.  This implies that this parameter represents the maximum delay introduced by the micro DTX optimized scheduler. It may be overwritten per NRDRB.    Note: Value 0 disables the maximum retention delay.

Parameter name: PRB threshold for micro DTX optimized scheduler
Description: This parameter indicates the minimum load of the cell in percent to trigger the scheduling of current bundles of DL data. This mechanism is used to avoid packet congestion for UEs with high throughput.  The load is computed based on the number of PRBs for PDSCH spanning over one or several slots that will be needed to transmit the buffered data compared to the number of PRBs available for PDSCH in this slot.

Parameter name: Rounding factor for micro DTX optimized scheduler
Description: This parameter indicates the rounding factor for determination of common slot for scheduling in multi-cell synchronization for micro-DTX optimized scheduler.

Parameter name: Rounding offset for micro DTX optimized scheduler
Description: This parameter indicates the rounding offset for determination of common slot for scheduling in multi-cell synchronization for micro-DTX optimized scheduler.

Parameter name: Multi cell synchronization enabled in micro-DTX optimized schedule
Description: This parameter enables/disables multi cell synchronization in micro-DTX optimized scheduler.    This parameter is ignored if NRCELL.actEnhDtxOptimizedScheduler is set to FALSE.

Parameter name: RLC status PDU support enabled in micro-DTX optimized schedule
Description: This parameter enables/disables RLC status PDU support in micro-DTX optimized scheduler.    This parameter is ignored if NRCELL.actEnhDtxOptimizedScheduler is set to FALSE.
This parameter indicates the duration within which, if the number of SCG failures (in NRCELL.nrOfScgFailures) is reported, the SgNB Release shall be triggered.
The parameter defines the dynamic BLER target algorithm to be used from either MAD algorithm or 2-region algorithm.

Parameter name: Enable replace cell selection with CA capability
Description: This parameter indicates whether the FR1 replacement cell needs to have the CA capability to be selected for SgNB addition (during NSA initial access) or not.  It is used during SgNB addition and used by the gNB only when the reported cell (i.e. the current NRCELL instance) is a part of a SgNB addition request message and that reported cell can support CA.
This parameter gathers parameters related to EIRP control

This parameter indicates the minimum guaranteed budget that shall be available in any EIRP control window step size.  If NRCELL.eirpControl.minGuaranteedBudgetRatioMode corresponds to actualEirpBudgetRatio, then this parameter is relative to the power reduction factor of each cell segment.  If NRCELL.eirpControl.minGuaranteedBudgetRatioMode corresponds to maxPowerBudgetRatio, then this parameter is relative to the maximum transmitted power and is common to all cell segments. In the latter case, if the configured ratio is greater than the power reduction factor of one cell segment, then the ratio indicated by this parameter may not be guaranteed for that cell segment.
This parameter indicates the mode applicable for the minimum guaranteed budget ratio of EIRP control.
This parameter indicates the minimum significant normalized beam gain to be considered for side lobes in a cell segment compared to Gmlb

Parameter name: Number of cell segment edges in azimuth
Description: The parameter indicates the number of cell segment minus 1 in the azimuth direction over which EIRP is monitored.

Parameter name: Number of cell segment edges in elevation
Description: The parameter indicates the number of cell segment minus 1 in the elevation direction over which EIRP is monitored.
This parameter enables or disables proportional fair scheduling weight factor correction for EIRP control based on the power reduction factor applicable to the serving beam

This parameter indicates a boundary in azimuth (segmentAzimuthEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentElevationEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge0 as an upper azimuth edge cover azimuth range from -90 degree to segmentAzimuthEdge0 while the cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge0 as a lower azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge0 to segmentAzimuthEdge1 if configured, to 90 degree otherwise. If not configured, there is a single cell segment from -90 degree to 90 degree.

This parameter indicates a boundary in azimuth (segmentAzimuthEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentElevationEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge1 as an upper azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge0 degree to segmentAzimuthEdge1 while the cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge1 as a lower azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge1 to segmentAzimuthEdge2 if configured, to 90 degree otherwise.

This parameter indicates a boundary in azimuth (segmentAzimuthEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentElevationEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge2 as an upper azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge1 degree to segmentAzimuthEdge2 while the cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge2 as a lower azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge2 to segmentAzimuthEdge3 if configured, to 90 degree otherwise.

This parameter indicates a boundary in azimuth (segmentAzimuthEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentElevationEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge3 as an upper azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge2 degree to segmentAzimuthEdge3 while the cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge3 as a lower azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge3 to segmentAzimuthEdge4 if configured, to 90 degree otherwise.

This parameter indicates a boundary in azimuth (segmentAzimuthEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentElevationEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge4 as an upper azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge3 degree to segmentAzimuthEdge4 while the cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge4 as a lower azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge4 to segmentAzimuthEdge5 if configured, to 90 degree otherwise.

This parameter indicates a boundary in azimuth (segmentAzimuthEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentElevationEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge5 as an upper azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge4 degree to segmentAzimuthEdge5 while the cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge5 as a lower azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge5 to segmentAzimuthEdge6 if configured, to 90 degree otherwise.

This parameter indicates a boundary in azimuth (segmentAzimuthEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentElevationEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge6 as an upper azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge5 degree to segmentAzimuthEdge6 while the cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge6 as a lower azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge6 to segmentAzimuthEdge7 if configured, to 90 degree otherwise.

This parameter indicates a boundary in azimuth (segmentAzimuthEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentElevationEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge7 as an upper azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge6 degree to segmentAzimuthEdge7 while the cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge7 as a lower azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge7 to segmentAzimuthEdge8 if configured, to 90 degree otherwise.

This parameter indicates a boundary in azimuth (segmentAzimuthEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentElevationEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge8 as an upper azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge7 degree to segmentAzimuthEdge8 while the cell segments sharing segmentAzimuthEdge8 as a lower azimuth edge cover azimuth range from segmentAzimuthEdge8 to 90 degree.

This parameter indicates a boundary in elevation (segmentElevationEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentAzimuthEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentElevationEdge0 as a lower elevation edge cover elevation range from 90 degree(i.e. towards ground) to segmentElevationEdge0 while the cell segments sharing segmentElevationEdge0 as an upper elevation edge cover elevation range from segmentElevationEdge0 to segmenElevationEdge1 if configured, to -90 degree (i.e. towards sky) otherwise. If not configured, there is a single cell segment from 90 degree (i.e. towards ground) to -90 degree (i.e. towards sky).

This parameter indicates a boundary in Elevation (segmentElevationEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentAzimuthEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentElevationEdge1 as a lower elevation edge cover elevation range from segmentElevationEdge0 degree to segmentElevationEdge1 while the cell segments sharing segmentElevationEdge1 as an upper elevation edge cover elevation range from segmentElevationEdge1 to segmentElevationEdge2 if configured, to -90 degree otherwise.

This parameter indicates a boundary in Elevation (segmentElevationEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentAzimuthEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentElevationEdge2 as a lower elevation edge cover elevation range from segmentElevationEdge1 degree to segmentElevationEdge2 while the cell segments sharing segmentElevationEdge2 as an upper elevation edge cover elevation range from segmentElevationEdge2 to segmentElevationEdge3 if configured, to -90 degree otherwise.

This parameter indicates a boundary in Elevation (segmentElevationEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentAzimuthEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentElevationEdge3 as a lower elevation edge cover elevation range from segmentElevationEdge2 degree to segmentElevationEdge3 while the cell segments sharing segmentElevationEdge3 as an upper elevation edge cover elevation range from segmentElevationEdge3 to segmentElevationEdge4 if configured, to -90 degree otherwise.

This parameter indicates a boundary in Elevation (segmentElevationEdge) between two consecutive cell segments sharing the same segmentAzimuthEdge index. The cell segments sharing segmentElevationEdge4 as a lower elevation edge cover elevation range from segmentElevationEdge3 degree to segmentElevationEdge4 while the cell segments sharing segmentElevationEdge4 as an upper elevation edge cover elevation range from segmentElevationEdge4 to -90 degree.

Parameter name: List of EIRP control power reduction factor per cell segment
Description: This parameter is a list with one element per cell segment in the grid, i.e. for a normal cell (NRBTS.NRCELL.actSuperCell = false): (NRCELL.eirpControl.numOfSegmentElevationEdges + 1) x (NRCELL.eirpControl.numOfSegmentAzimuthEdges + 1) and for a SuperCell (NRBTS.NRCELL.actSuperCell = true):  number of elements = number of supercell subcells. Each element indicates the power reduction factor to be applied to the maximum transmitted power to obtain the actual EIRP threshold in the considered cell segment
This parameter indicates the time averaging sliding window over which EIRP control is applied

Parameter name: EIRP control time averaging window step size
Description: This parameter indicates the step size of the time averaging sliding window over which EIRP control is applied
This parameter indicates the list of emergency area IDs for the NR Cell

Parameter name: Forced LTE fallback in case NR emergency call fail
Description: This parameter indicates if LTE emergency fallback is forced in case a NR emergency call fails.  This parameter overcomes the deactivation of the emergency service fallback to LTE via NRBTS.actEmergencyFallback and deactivation of normal voice call fallback to LTE via NRBTS.actNormVCFallback.
This parameter indicates if emergency call for limited service mode is supported or not.  If supported, the gNB will broadcast in SIB1 IMS EmergencySupport IE.
This parameter gathers parameters to configure restrictions for emergency call

Parameter name: Ignore emergency call mobility restrictions list
Description: This parameter indicates if the mobility restrictions list in case of emergency call shall be ignored or enforced.  It applies to 5G to LTE handover only. In case it is equal to TRUE, the gNB handles the mobility restrictions list as if it has not received that list.

Parameter name: Emergency call inter PLMN HO allowed
Description: This parameter indicates if inter PLMN handover for emergency call is allowed or not.  It applies to 5G to LTE and intra-RAT handover (inter-gNB, intra-gNB and intra-DU handover).
This parameter indicates which fallback mode is used for the emergency services
This parameter allows to change the azimuth for artificial load in EMF test mode (e.g. NRCELL.emfAzimuth = 0, means horizontal direction perpendicular to antenna panel).

This parameter is a list of pointers to the child NRBEAM_EMF instance(s) representing the beam profile(s) to be used to generate artificial load for EMF test mode (if NRCELL.actEmfTestMode is set to TRUE).  Example:  NRBEAM_EMF-1

This parameter allows to change the elevation for artificial load in EMF test mode (e.g. NRCELL.emfElevation = 0, means vertical direction perpendicular to antenna panel).    Note: For NRCELL.emfElevation, angles between -90 and 0 degrees towards the sky, angles between 0 and +90 degrees are below horizon.

Parameter name: Target total load for EMF test mode
Description: This parameter indicates the target total load (normal + artificial load) for creating artificial load in the cell. The artificial load is created using the selected beams.    When normal load is below the target load, the artificial load is added up to the target load.  When normal load is greater than or equal to the target load, no artificial load is added.  If this parameter is equal to 0, then no artificial load shall be created.

This parameter indicates the EN-DC synchronization status    Configuring this parameter during cell addition or cell removal will not provoke a gNB reset.  Updating this parameter will provoke a gNB reset.  Note: In SBTS, changing this parameter will require only a 5G RAT restart.
This parameter indicates the energy saving state of the NR cell.  It is set by the gNB.
Range and step: notEnergySaving (0), energySaving (1), reducedEnergySaving (2), switchingOff (3), switchingOffRTX (4), switchingOnTX (5)

Description: This parameter indicates if the primary path in UL for SCG split bearer and the initial DL traffic are forced to be over LTE.    Note1 [uplink, for UEs capable of UL data split]: This parameter overrides the value chosen for NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.ulDataPath if it is equal to TRUE.  More precisely, if this parameter is equal to TRUE, then, for a NRDRB instance associated with the concerned bearer:  - If NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.ulDataPath is equal to 4 (corresponding to ulOverLteNr_PrimaryPathOverNr), then the value of NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.ulDataPath is forced to 3 (corresponding to ulOverLteNr_PrimaryPathOverLte)  - If NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.ulDataPath is equal to 0 or 1 or 3 (corresponding respectively to ulOverLte, ulOverNr, ulOverLteNr_PrimaryPathOverLte) then there is no change.    Note2 [uplink, for UEs not capable of UL data split] : This parameter overrides the value chosen for NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.ulDataPathForUlSplitNotCapableUe.  More precisely, if this parameter is equal to TRUE, then, for a NRDRB instance associated with the concerned bearer:  - If NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.ulDataPath is equal to 3 or 4 (corresponding to ulOverLteNr_PrimaryPathOverLte, ulOverLteNr_PrimaryPathOverNr) and NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.ulDataPathForUlSplitNotCapableUe is equal to 1 (corresponding to ulPrimaryPathOverNr), then the value of NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.ulDataPathForUlSplitNotCapableUe is forced to 0 (corresponding to ulPrimaryPathOverLte)    Note3 [downlink]: This parameter overrides the value chosen for NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.actPrioritizeX2AfterInactivity and NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.initialDLTrafficRouting, depending on value of NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.dlDataSplitMode if it is equal to TRUE.  More precisely, if this parameter is equal to TRUE, then, for all the NRDRB instance(s):  - if NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.dlDataSplitMode is equal to 2 (corresponding to dlOverF1UX2U), then the value of NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.actPrioritizeX2AfterInactivity is forced to TRUE and the value of NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.initialDLTrafficRouting is forced to 1 (corresponding to initDLoverX2U)  - if NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.dlDataSplitMode is equal to 0 or 1 (corresponding respectively to dlOverF1U, dlOverX2U) then there is no change.    Note4 : If parameter is not configured or is equal to FALSE, then the bearer behavior is aligned with the legacy NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.actPrioritizeX2AfterInactivity and NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.initialDLTrafficRouting value for downlink and with the legacy NRDRB.nsaDrbParam.ulDataPath value for uplink of the associated NRDRB instance.
This parameter determines the appropriate counter histogram range (set), which should be aligned with the expected size of the cell from preceding network planning.
This parameter indicates the external antenna feeder loss for the purpose of EIRP monitoring.  It shall be configured if the cell is associated with a radio unit using external antennas.

This parameter indicates the external antenna gain for the purpose of EIRP monitoring. Feeder losses shall be configured separately.  It shall be configured if the cell is associated with a radio unit using external antenna if no msi file is provided.

Parameter name: First PDCCH monitoring occasion of paging occasion
Description: This parameter indicates the list of symbols for the first PDCCH monitoring occasion of each paging occasion in a paging frame.    Setting of this parameter needs to follow the Configuration Guide for paging parameters.

This parameter indicates the L3 filter coefficient value for RS type SS/PBCH blocks and measurement quantities RSRP from the L1 filter(s).  If this parameter is not configured, then the considered filter coefficient is 4 (corresponding to fc4).

This parameter indicates the L3 filter coefficient value for RS type SS/PBCH blocks and measurement quantities RSRQ from the L1 filter(s).  If this parameter is not configured, then the considered filter coefficient is 4 (corresponding to fc4).
This structure gathers distinguished names (DN) parameters for 5QI specific cell level override of DRX.

Parameter name: New Radio 5QI to DRB Profile Mapping distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated NRDRB_5QI instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRDRB_5QI-2  NRDRB_5QI-2

Parameter name: New Radio Discontinuous Reception Transmission distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated NRDRX instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRDRX-2  NRDRX-2

Parameter name: Forbid data forwarding via DRB level tunnel in Intra-NR handover via NG
Description: This parameter indicates whether data forwarding via DRB level tunnel is forbidden during incoming Intra-NR handover via NG.  If it is equal to TRUE, then data forwarding via DRB level tunnel is forbidden for incoming Intra-NR handover via NG (i.e. only PDU session level data forwarding tunnel could be provided).  If it is equal to FALSE, then data forwarding via DRB level tunnel could be provided when applicable.  In case the core network does not support data forwarding via DRB level tunnel, it is suggested to set this parameter to TRUE. In this case, it is also recommended to set NRBTS.actForceFullRRCConfigurationSaHo to 'onlyNgHo' or 'enabled' to avoid possible small delay of DL data submission to upper layer after UE access target cell.

This parameter indicates the RU operation mode on FR2 radio.  The following operation modes at a system level are defined:  - 'One_Sector_1600MHz_IBW_2T2R_SU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured as a single sector with iBW of 1600 MHz. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies shall be within 1600MHz. 2T2R Single User MIMO is used.  - 'One_Sector_1600MHz_IBW_4T4R_SU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured as a single sector with iBW of 1600 MHz. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies shall be within 1600MHz. 4T4R Single User MIMO is used.  - 'One_Sector_3200MHz_IBW_2T2R_SU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured as a single sector with iBW of 3200 MHz. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies shall be within 3200 MHz. 2T2R Single User MIMO is used.  - 'Two_Sector_1600MHz_PER_SECTOR_IBW_2T2R_SU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured as being in 2 sectors with a maximum iBW of 1600 MHz per sector. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies in an individual sector shall be within 1600 MHz. 2T2R Single User MIMO is used.  - 'One_Sector_1600MHz_IBW_Two_User_2T2R_MU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured a single sector with iBW of 1600 MHz per sector. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies shall be within 1600MHz. 2T2R Two User Multi-User MIMO is used.  - 'One_Sector_800MHz_IBW_8T8R_SU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured as a single sector with iBW of 800 MHz. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies shall be within 800MHz. 8T8R Single User MIMO is used.  - 'Two_Sector_800MHz_PER_SECTOR_IBW_4T4R_SU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured as being in 2 sectors with a maximum iBW of 800 MHz per sector. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies in an individual sector shall be within 800 MHz. 4T4R Single User MIMO is used.  - 'One_Sector_800MHz_IBW_Two_User_4T4R_MU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured a single sector with iBW of 800 MHz per sector. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies shall be within 800MHz. 4T4R Two User Multi-User MIMO is used.  - 'Four_Sector_800MHz_PER_SECTOR_IBW_2T2R_SU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured as being in 4 sectors with a maximum iBW of 800 MHz per sector. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies in an individual sector shall be within 800 MHz. 2T2R Single User MIMO is used.  - 'One_Sector_800MHz_IBW_Four_User_2T2R_MU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured a single sector with iBW of 800 MHz per sector. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies shall be within 800MHz. 2T2R Four User Multi-User MIMO is used.  - 'Two_Sector_800MHz_PER_SECTOR_IBW_Two_User_2T2R_MU_MIMO' meaning the NRCELL instances under the RU are configured as being in 2 sectors with a maximum iBW of 800 MHz per sector. Thus, all the NRCELL frequencies in an individual sector shall be within 800 MHz. 2T2R Two User Multi-User MIMO is used.    Configuring this parameter during cell addition might provoke cell reset - gNB takes decision of reset necessity.  Updating this parameter might provoke a FR2 radio reset-- gNB takes decision of reset necessity.  Removal of this parameter during cell deletion will not provoke a gNB reset.  Note: In SBTS, changing this parameter will require only a 5G RAT restart.

Parameter name: List of references to Flexi Radio Modules
Description: This list identifies the radio modules associated with the New Radio cell. The format is 'FR-x' where x refers to the Radio Module identifier in the BTS profile.

This parameter indicates the frame start offset for the NR Cell.  The defined offset is observed as a shift of the frame start at the Air Interface with the reference to the BTS clock (as best represented by its 1PPS output).  If both this parameter and SYNC.manualFrameTimingAdjustment are configured, then this parameter takes precedence as the applied shift of the Air Interface timing.    This parameter is ignored if FEATCADM.actCellTimingOffset is equal to FALSE, for eCPRI cells.  This parameter is ignored if FEATCADM.actCellTimingOffsetCpriN is equal to FALSE, for CPRI-N cells.
This parameter defines the Frequency Band Indicator NR
This parameter indicates the gap offset of the gap pattern with MGRP contained in the field MGRP

Parameter name: GBR scheduling congestion detection for Radio Admission Control
Description: This parameter determines if GBR time domain scheduling congestion at L2 drives GBR load to 100%.  If GBR load is set to 100%, then no further GBR DRBs are admitted until congestion is no longer present

This parameter indicates the frequency position of the SS/PBCH Block by using either the Global Synchronization Channel Number (GSCN) or the Absolute Radio Frequency Channel Number SSB (absoluteFrequencySSB).  It is based on the parameter in 3GPP 38.104. Even if the full value range for the parameter is [3...3279165], the actual value range depends on used configuration. Configuration specific value range depends on the used NR Operating Band, carrier bandwidth, Sub Carrier Spacing (SCS), the context of the parameter (GSCN or SS/PBCH ARFCN as shown below) and all BWPs configured in the cell. Please refer to 38.104 specification for details.    The following constraints are checked by the gNB before to bring up the cells (if the check fails, an alarm with supplementary information is raised and the cell is out of order):  - All BWPs configured and used in the cell must fully include at least the SS/PBCH bandwidth.  - When the SIB1 is broadcasted in the cell (SA or SA+NSA or NSA cell with NRCELL.actSib1ForNsaCell set to TRUE), all BWPs potentially activated in the UEs, and where the SIB1 should be received, must fully include the CORESET(0) bandwidth (which is handling SIB1 transmission(s)). Before to get the SIB1, the idle UEs use the CORESET(0) bandwidth. After the SIB1 decoding, the idle UEs use the initial BWP defined in the SIB1 to get the RRC configuration. RRC configured UEs use only their active BWP initialized in the RRC setup or reconfiguration message and updated through DCI bandwidth part switch (if supported).  - When a BWP is configured with a Search space linked to the CORESET(0), then this BWP must fully include the CORESET(0) bandwidth.  - When a BWP is configured with a UE-Specific search space and the CSI-RS for Beam Management are activated (below or above the SS/PBCH bandwidth) in the cell, the minimum size of the CSI-RS bandwidth (24 RBs) bandwidth must be fully included in this BWP.  - When the PRB blanking feature is activated, the SS/PBCH bandwidth, and potentially the CORESET(0) and CSI-RS for Beam Management bandwidths according to BWP and cell configuration, must not overlap the blanked areas.  - When several dedicated BWPs (BWP type: power saving or dedicated) are configured and not activated (NRCELL.actPowerSavingBWP, NRBTS.actMultipleDedicatedBWPs), the gNB selects the largest BWP starting with the lowest Common Resource Block (CRB) and with the lowest cell BWP identifier and defined with a BWP type set to dedicated, as the default dedicated BWP.    Values 0...2: Special values that can be used to locate the SS/PBCH bandwidth with respect to the carrier bandwidth and all BWPs configured and used in the cell as follows:  - 0 : the GSCN is the smallest value allowed in order to fit all relevant constraints above.  - 1 : the GSCN is as close as possible to the NR-ARFCN of the cell in order to fit all relevant constraints above.  - 2 : the GSCN is the highest value allowed in order to fit all relevant constraints above.    Values 3...26639: Explicit GSCN value based on synchronization raster as defined in 3GPP.    Values 26640...3279165: SS/PBCH ARFCN value directly for cells with NRCELL.cellDepType equal to 'NSA', 'NR-DC-SN' or 'NR-DC-SN+NSA'.    Setting of this parameter needs to follow the Configuration Guide for GSCN parameters.

Parameter name: Percentage of UEs for idle mode mobility steering for EN-DC
Description: This parameter indicates the percentage of UEs to be selected for EN-DC aware idle mode traffic steering.    This parameter is used in scenarios without idle mode mobility profile. However, if a mobility profile is preferred, the equivalent parameter is NRMOIMP_SA.idleMMEnDcSteeringPercentageOfUes.

Parameter name: SSB Frequency for idle mode mobility steering for EN-DC
Description: This parameter indicates the target SSB frequency to be used in evaluating if a UE is a valid candidate for idle mode traffic steering.    This parameter is used in scenarios without idle mode mobility profile. However, if a mobility profile is preferred, the equivalent parameter is NRMOIMP_SA.idleMMEnDcSteeringSsbFrequency.

Parameter name: Weighted round robin for idle mode mobility steering enabled for EN-DC
Description: This parameter enables/disables weighted round robin for primary target selection for EN-DC aware idle mode traffic steering.    This parameter is used in scenarios without idle mode mobility profile. However, if a mobility profile is preferred, the equivalent parameter is NRMOIMP_SA.idleMMEnDcSteeringWRREnabled.

Parameter name: Serving carrier weight factor for idle mode mobility steering
Description: This parameter indicates the serving carrier weight factor for DL CA aware / non-CA aware idle mode mobility steering.
This parameter indicates the selected algorithm for idle mode mobility steering.  Note: CA aware means DL CA aware algorithm.
Range and step: non CA aware (0), CA aware (1), UL CA aware (2), UL and DL CA aware (3)

Parameter name: Percentage of UEs for idle mode mobility steering
Description: This parameter indicates the percentage of UEs to be selected for idle mode mobility steering.

Parameter name: Weighted round robin for idle mode mobility steering enabled
Description: This parameter enables/disables weighted round robin for primary target selection for idle mode Mobility steering

Parameter name: WRR for CA eligible secondary targets in IMM steering
Description: This parameter enables/disables weighted round robin priority assignment for CA eligible secondary target frequencies in UL CA and/or DL CA aware idle mode mobility steering
Range and step: Disabled (0), DL CA aware (1), UL CA aware (2), UL and DL CA aware (3)

Parameter name: SSB measurement timing offset for inter-frequency measurement
Description: This parameter indicates the SSB offset configuration for the inter-frequency SSB frequency.  It is based on timing reference of SpCell and is given in number of subframes.

This parameter indicates the inactive SS/PBCH indexes in the configured SS/PBCH indexes for FR2 SA cells.  It is a bit mask with Bit 0 (LSB) corresponding to SS/PBCH Index 0, Bit 1 corresponding to SS/PBCH Index 1, ... Bit 63 corresponding to SS/PBCH Index 63.  If Bit x is equal to 1, SS/PBCH Index x is inactive if the SS/PBCH is configured (indicated by RRC IE: ssb-PositionsInBurst).  If Bit x is equal to 0, SS/PBCH Index x is active if the SS/PBCH is configured (indicated by RRC IE: ssb-PositionsInBurst).  To set any Bit x to 1, it is needed to know whether the corresponding SS/PBCH index is configured or not.    For a FR2 SA cell which has (NRCELL.tddFrameStructure.frameStructureType equal to 'semiStatic' and NRCELL.tddFrameStructure.ulDlDataSlotRatio equal to '1/4' and NRCELL.prachConfigurationIndex equal to a value in the range [112...143]) and which belongs to a NRCELLGRP instance which has NRCELLGRP.numberOfTransmittedSsBlocks greater than or equal to '32 beams':  - If NRCELL.tddFrameStructure.guardPeriodLength is equal to '2Symbols', then the value (Bit63-Bit0) of this parameter is recommended to be equal to 0x0000 0000 0000 0000 respectively [0000000000000000 0000000000000000 0000000000000000 0000000000000000]  - If NRCELL.tddFrameStructure.guardPeriodLength is equal to '6Symbols', then the value (Bit63-Bit0) of this parameter is recommended to be equal to 0x8B00 D884 2100 C210 respectively [1000101100000000 1101100010000100 0010000100000000 1100001000010000]  - If NRCELL.tddFrameStructure.guardPeriodLength is equal to '10Symbols', then the value (Bit63-Bit0) of this parameter is recommended to be equal to 0x0800 F884 2100 F210 respectively [0000100000000000 1111100010000100 0010000100000000 1111001000010000]
Range and step: bits mask: SS/PBCH Index 0 (0), SS/PBCH Index 1 (1), SS/PBCH Index 2 (2), SS/PBCH Index 3 (3), SS/PBCH Index 4 (4), SS/PBCH Index 5 (5), SS/PBCH Index 6 (6), SS/PBCH Index 7 (7), SS/PBCH Index 8 (8), SS/PBCH Index 9 (9), SS/PBCH Index 10 (10), SS/PBCH Index 11 (11), SS/PBCH Index 12 (12), SS/PBCH Index 13 (13), SS/PBCH Index 14 (14), SS/PBCH Index 15 (15), SS/PBCH Index 16 (16), SS/PBCH Index 17 (17), SS/PBCH Index 18 (18), SS/PBCH Index 19 (19), SS/PBCH Index 20 (20), SS/PBCH Index 21 (21), SS/PBCH Index 22 (22), SS/PBCH Index 23 (23), SS/PBCH Index 24 (24), SS/PBCH Index 25 (25), SS/PBCH Index 26 (26), SS/PBCH Index 27 (27), SS/PBCH Index 28 (28), SS/PBCH Index 29 (29), SS/PBCH Index 30 (30), SS/PBCH Index 31 (31), SS/PBCH Index 32 (32), SS/PBCH Index 33 (33), SS/PBCH Index 34 (34), SS/PBCH Index 35 (35), SS/PBCH Index 36 (36), SS/PBCH Index 37 (37), SS/PBCH Index 38 (38), SS/PBCH Index 39 (39), SS/PBCH Index 40 (40), SS/PBCH Index 41 (41), SS/PBCH Index 42 (42), SS/PBCH Index 43 (43), SS/PBCH Index 44 (44), SS/PBCH Index 45 (45), SS/PBCH Index 46 (46), SS/PBCH Index 47 (47), SS/PBCH Index 48 (48), SS/PBCH Index 49 (49), SS/PBCH Index 50 (50), SS/PBCH Index 51 (51), SS/PBCH Index 52 (52), SS/PBCH Index 53 (53), SS/PBCH Index 54 (54), SS/PBCH Index 55 (55), SS/PBCH Index 56 (56), SS/PBCH Index 57 (57), SS/PBCH Index 58 (58), SS/PBCH Index 59 (59), SS/PBCH Index 60 (60), SS/PBCH Index 61 (61), SS/PBCH Index 62 (62), SS/PBCH Index 63 (63)

Parameter name: K1 value increase for UL CA
Description: This parameter indicates how much the K1 value is increased in case inter-band FDD + FDD uplink carrier aggregation is activated.
Range and step: K1 not increased (0), K1 increased by 1 slot (1)

Parameter name: PUSCH preparation time increase for UL CA
Description: This parameter indicates the K2 increase to allow larger UE PUSCH preparation procedure time when the cell is a FR1 TDD cell with UL CA configured. This provides enough UE preparation time for UCI over PUSCH.
This structure defines the parameters to configure the interfering TDD frame structure.
This parameter defines the type of the interfering TDD frame structure of the bordering country.
This parameter defines the length in the OFDM symbols of the guard period of the interfering TDD frame structure of the bordering country.

Parameter name: Interfering LTE to NR frame shift
Description: This parameter defines the LTE to NR frame shift in ms of the interfering TDD frame structure of the bordering country.
This parameter indicates the Subcarrier Spacing (SCS) value of the interfering (e.g. neighboring country's) 5G carrier.
This parameter indicates the TD LTE uplink and downlink configuration of the interfering TDD frame structure of the bordering country.

Parameter name: Interfering TDD frame muting bilateral agreement
Description: This parameter indicates if there is a bilateral agreement with the neighboring country's operator related to interfering TDD frames.  If it is equal to TRUE, only DL interfering symbols are muted (blanked). If it is equal to FALSE, both UL and DL interfering symbols are muted (blanked).

Parameter name: Interfering UL to DL logical data slot ratio
Description: This parameter defines the ratio of the UL / DL logical data slots of the interfering TDD frame structure of the bordering country.

Parameter name: Initial number of secondary cells to activate
Description: This parameter indicates the initial number of secondary cells to activate jointly when the downlink buffer check triggers secondary cell activation and there is no active secondary cell yet.    If this parameter is not configured or is equal to 0 or the value in this parameter exceeds the number of configured secondary cells, the gNB activates all the secondary cells available for activation

This parameter defines the initial preamble power.  The recommended value for this parameter is +10dB above noise level. For FR1, it is -104 (corresponding to -104dBm) and for FR2 it is -96 (corresponding to -96dBm)
This structure gathers the inter rank switch block threshold values for TDD FR1 only.

Parameter name: High bler threshold of inter rank switch block
Description: This parameter indicates the high BLER percent threshold for inter rank switch block.

Parameter name: Low bler threshold of inter rank switch block
Description: This parameter indicates the low BLER percent threshold for inter rank switch block.

Parameter name: MCS threshold 1 of inter rank switch block
Description: This parameter indicates the MCS threshold 1 (low risk MCS for filtering rank switch) for inter rank switch block.

Parameter name: MCS threshold 2 of inter rank switch block
Description: This parameter indicates the MCS threshold 2 (high risk MCS for filtering rank switch) for inter rank switch block.
This parameter determines whether intra frequency cell reselection is allowed  Intra frequency reselection is not allowed for Supplemental DL Cells.
This parameter indicates the ID of the Local Cell Resource. It corresponds to the rightmost 14 to 4 bits of NRCELL.nrCellIdentity
This structure gathers parameters relating to LCS.
This parameter indicates the antenna opening degree, i.e. the degree having the direction of antenna orientation as the center. 0 degree for North and increase by clockwise. 0, 1, 2...360.
This parameter indicates the antenna orientation.
This parameter indicates the radius error of the geographical area identity (GAI).
This parameter indicates whether location information is available (value 'inService') or unavailable (value 'outOfService').
This parameter indicates whether the repeater connection has been identified (value 'withRepeater') or not (value 'withoutRepeater').
This structure gathers the angle offsets triplet of LCS with respect to the global coordinate system (GCS).
This parameter indicates the orienting direction of LCS for the bearing angle 'alpha' with respect to GCS.
This parameter indicates the orienting direction of LCS for the downtilt angle 'beta' with respect to GCS.
This parameter indicates the orienting direction of LCS for the slant angle 'gamma' with respect to GCS.

Parameter name: Limited Beams Per Stream Per Slot
Description: This parameter defines the limited number of beams per stream per slot is supported by RU for cells whose bandwidth is less than or equal to 20MHz. If this parameter is set to 'true', gNB shall always apply SSB beams for PDCCH for both UL and DL grant.  This parameter shall be set to 'true' for the cell whose bandwidth is less then or equal to 20MHz, if the cell is deployed on RF6.2 RUs.    -Configuring this parameter during cell addition might provoke 5G RAT reset  -Updating this parameter will provoke 5G RAT reset.  -Removal of this parameter during cell deletion will not provoke 5G RAT reset.  -gNB takes decision of reset necessity.

This parameter indicates the long PUCCH configuration type.    The supported values are:  - 'duActCaPucchConfig': PUCCH resource pools allocation at FDD cell setup according to the DU specific CA activation parameters configuration.  - 'nonCaPucchConfig': PUCCH resource pools allocation at FDD cell setup optimized for non-CA FDD cells when CA functionality is activated on DU level.    Note: This parameter is only applicable for FDD cells (NRCELL.cellTechnology equal to 'FDD') and configured with long PUCCH (NRCELL.pucchModeSelect equal to 'longPucch') when FR1 CA is enabled, i.e. NRDU.flexibleCAMode is equal to a value different from 'BasicCAMode' for the NRDU instance matching the current NRCELL instance.

This parameter indicates the amount of SR resource to be reserved for low latency when adaptive SR functionality is being used.  Reservation is done as a percentage of the total capacity of the SR pool.  Reservation for low latency is used to allow some number of UEs to be allocated with shorter SR periods even if the main pool is the pool with longer SR period.  Reservation for low latency is kept in a given pool until certain threshold (defined by adaptive SR mechanism) is reached. If the load in the cell (in terms for occupied SR resource in a pool) is above this threshold, then reservation for low latency is released (UEs using that reservation are reallocated to the pool with longer SR period and new incoming UEs are not allocated to shorter pool even if reservation for low latency is not yet fully used).    If this parameter is not configured, then the system automatically reserves some number of resources for low latency.  If this parameter is set to 0, then there is no reservation for low latency.

Parameter name: Lower MCS threshold for power backoff
Description: The parameter indicates the lower threshold of MCS for the power back-off algorithm.

This parameter indicates the mode for the LTE-NR dynamic spectrum sharing.    If this parameter is set to 'none', the LTE-NR spectrum sharing is deactivated for the NR cell.  This parameter is always set to 'none' for supplemental DL cells (FDD).    If this parameter is set to 'DL_CRS_TDM_UL_FDM', the CRS rate matching based spectrum sharing will be used.    If this parameter is set to 'DSS_Phase_3', LTE-NR DSS with improved allocation Range and LTE-NR DSS with superfast coordination can be used.

Parameter name: Time offset between the LTE PCell and the NR cell
Description: This parameter indicates the actual absolute time offset between the LTE PCell and the NR Cell.    Configuring this parameter during cell addition might provoke gNB restart - gNB takes the decision as regards restart necessity.  Updating this parameter will provoke gNB restart.  Removal of this parameter during cell deletion will not provoke gNB restart.  Note: In SBTS, changing this parameter will require only a 5G RAT restart.
This parameter indicates the massive MIMO (mMIMO) antenna array mode on mMIMO MAA.    Updating this parameter will provoke a cell reset.
Range and step: Full 64TRX Array (4x8x2) (0), Left 32TRX Array (4x4x2) (1), Right 32TRX Array (4x4x2) (2), Top 32TRX Array (2x8x2) (3), Bottom 32TRX Array (2x8x2) (4), Top 16TRX Array (1x8x2) (5), Bottom 16TRX Array (1x8x2) (6), Full 32TRX Array (2x8x2) (7)

Description: This parameter indicates the maximum percentage of total available radio resources in uplink and downlink for both non-GBR and GBR bearer traffic checked at admission control for new GBR request. New GBR request for which sum of its estimated resource usage and current total GBR resource usage in the cell is above the threshold is rejected or triggers resource pre-emption.

Parameter name: Maximum number of HARQ attempts for uplink PUSCH slot aggregation
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of HARQ attempts for both 2x and 4x Slot Aggregation (SAg) transmissions for 5QI1 VoNR. Along with indicating the maximum number of HARQs for 2x and 4x SAg, this indirectly indicates the number of slots that will be used worst case for transmission of a VoNR packet (slots = Max number of HARQs multiplied by 4 repetitions per bundle).

Parameter name: Max inital delta CQI value for VoNR UEs
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum initial Delta CQI value for VoNR UEs when the clamp is enabled (corresponding to NRCELL.actMaxInitDeltaCqiClampVoNR equal to TRUE).  This maximum initial Delta CQI value for VoNR UEs which is conservative in nature is considered to ensure that DLLA calculates conservative MCS values during the early phase of the session. It should ensure that BLER remains low while OLLA adjusts to the actual channel conditions. When the cell average delta CQI value is higher than this parameter, the gNB will use this parameter as initial Delta CQI value for VoNR UEs.

This parameter indicates the maximum percentage of radio resources that can be used for NBR traffic in uplink and downlink from the total available radio resources available for both non-GBR and GBR.  It corresponds to the percentage of radio resources that are available for NBR transmissions from the PDCCH, PDSCH, and PUSCH resources. PUCCH and PRACH resources are not controlled by this parameter.

Parameter name: Maximum number of users of 2 component carriers
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of users for which the gNB can allocate 2 component carriers in a PSCell.  This parameter is applicable only for NSA and NR-DC NR Cells.

Parameter name: Maximum number of users of 2 component carriers FR2 SA
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of CA FR2 SA users for which the gNB can allocate 2 component carriers in a PCell.  The gNB ensures that the number of UEs configured with 2CCs does not exceed this threshold. However, it considers also the available resources during calculation, so the actual amount of UEs configured with 2CCs can be lower than this configured threshold.  If this parameter is not configured, then the gNB does not limit the number of UEs in 2 CCs when calculating the cardinality of list of candidate SCells.

Parameter name: Maximum number of users of 3 to 4 component carriers
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of users for which the gNB can allocate 3 or 4 component carriers in a PSCell.  This parameter is applicable only for NSA and NR-DC NR Cells.

Parameter name: Maximum number of users of 3 to 4 component carriers FR2 SA
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of CA FR2 SA users for which the gNB can allocate 3 or 4 component carriers in a PCell.  The gNB ensures that the number of UEs configured with 3 to 4CCs does not exceed this threshold. However, it considers also the available resources during calculation, so the actual amount of UEs configured with 3-4CCs can be lower than this configured threshold.  If this parameter is not configured, then the gNB does not limit the number of UEs in 3 to 4 CCs when calculating the cardinality of list of candidate SCells.

Parameter name: Maximum number of users of 5 to 8 component carriers
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of users for which the gNB can allocate 5, 6,7 or 8 component carriers in a PSCell.  This parameter is applicable only for NSA and NR-DC NR Cells.

Parameter name: Maximum number of users of 5 to 8 component carriers FR2 SA
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of CA FR2 SA users for which the gNB can allocate 5, 6,7 or 8 component carriers in a PCell.  The gNB ensures that the number of UEs configured with 5 to 8CCs does not exceed this threshold. However, it considers also the available resources during calculation, so the actual amount of UEs configured with 5-8CCs can be lower than this configured threshold.  If this parameter is not configured, then the gNB does not limit the number of UEs in 5 to 8 CCs when calculating the cardinality of list of candidate SCells.

Parameter name: Maximum number of RRC connected users configured with carrier aggregation in a New Radio cell
Description: This parameter indicates the threshold for the maximum number of SA and NSA users configured with carrier aggregation in the FR1 New Radio cell.  This parameter is used by the radio admission control in the CU.    The actual maximum number of users configured with carrier aggregation depends on the available resources in the cell, shared among the users with and without carrier aggregation.

Parameter name: Maximum number of GBR data radio bearers in a New Radio cell for SA
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of GBR data radio bearers of active UEs operating in the New Radio Cell for SA.  This parameter is used by the radio admission control in the gNB-CU and the gNB-DU.

Parameter name: Maximum number of NBR data radio bearers in a New Radio cell
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of NBR configured nonGBR data radio bearers of active UEs operating in the New Radio Cell.  It is used by the radio admission control in the gNB-DU.

Parameter name: Maximum number of non-GBR data radio bearers in a New Radio cell for SA
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of non-GBR data radio bearers of active UEs operating in the New Radio Cell for SA.  This parameter is used by the radio admission control in the gNB-CU and the gNB-DU.

Parameter name: Maximum number of non-GBR data radio bearers in a NR cell for NR-DC-SN operation
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of non-GBR data radio bearers of active UEs operating in NR-DC-SN in the NR cell.  This parameter is used by the radio admission control in the gNB-CU and the gNB-DU. It is applicable only for PSCell users.

Parameter name: Maximum number of users in a NR cell for NR-DC-SN operation
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of users in the New Radio cell which may establish SCG connection for NR-DC operation.  The number of users is the sum of the NR-DC-SN PSCell allocations and the NR-DC-SN DL SCell allocations.  This parameter is used by the radio admission control in the CU.

Parameter name: Maximum number of RRC connected users in a New Radio cell for SA
Description: This parameter indicates the threshold for the maximum number of RRC connected UEs in the New Radio Cell.  This parameter is used by the radio admission control in the gNB-CU and the gNB-DU.

Parameter name: Maximum number of RRC connected reduced-capability users in a New Radio cell for SA
Description: This parameter indicates the threshold for the maximum number of RRC connected reduced-capability UEs in the New Radio Cell.  This parameter is used by the radio admission control in the gNB-CU and the gNB-DU.

Parameter name: Maximum number of secondary cell allocations in a cell
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum total number of secondary cell allocations for UEs in the cell.  This parameter is used by the radio admission control in the CU for SA, NSA and NR-DC-SN.    The actual maximum number of secondary cell allocation depends on the total number of users in the cell configured with or without carrier aggregation, or as secondary cell allocation.

Parameter name: Maximum number of FR1 UL CA UEs allowed to transmit in parallel in FR1 TDD PCell and FDD SCell overlapping UL slots
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of FR1 UL CA UEs that are allowed to transmit in parallel in FR1 TDD PCell and FDD SCell overlapping UL slots in order to increase the uplink peak throughput.  This parameter applies to FR1 UL CA TDD PCell only.  Note: If the NR Cell is mapped on a BBMOD hardware variant ABIL or ABILL and this parameter is greater than 0, then NRCELL.actAdaptiveReTxResMcsEnh shall be equal to TRUE.

Parameter name: Maximum number of users in a NR cell for NSA operation
Description: This parameter indicates the threshold for the maximum number of users in the New Radio cell which may establish SCG connection for NSA operation.  The number of users is the sum of the NSA PsCell allocations and the DL secondary cell allocations.  This parameter is used by the radio admission control.

Parameter name: Maximum number of users in a New Radio cell
Description: This parameter indicates the threshold for the maximum number of SA, NSA and NR-DC-SN users in the New Radio cell.  This parameter is used by the radio admission control in the CU.  Updating this parameter might provoke cell reset-- gNB takes decision of reset necessity.

Maximum number of paging records per paging message. This parameter is automatically recalculated by the gNB. If the number of paging records that can be transmitted over configured for paging slots is below the value set by this parameter the previously configured value will be overwritten according to the resulting value set by the gNB. Valid only for FR1.

Parameter name: Maximum number of PDSCH allocation per slot
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of PDSCH allocation per slot for FDD and TDD cells on FR1.  The actual maximum number that is possible may be smaller due to restrictions implied by various deployment and configuration options, such as:  - Baseband block configuration  - Cell technology  - Carrier Bandwidth  - PDSCH RAT0 RBG configuration  - PUCCH mode (long PUCCH, short PUCCH)  - PRB blanking  - DSS    If NRBTS.actScheUePooling is equal to TRUE or NRBTS.actBbPoolTddFr1 is equal to TRUE, for FDD cells or TDD FR1 cells, the recommended value of this parameter should be greater than 1.  For FDD and TDD cells on FR1, this parameter is ignored if NRCELL.actIncreasedFdmUsersPerSlot is equal to FALSE and UE pooling is disabled (NRBTS.actScheUePooling is equal to FALSE or NRBTS.actBbPoolTddFr1 is equal to FALSE).

Parameter name: Maximum number of PUSCH allocation per slot
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of PUSCH allocation per slot for FDD and TDD cells on FR1.  The actual maximum number that is possible may be smaller due to restrictions implied by various deployment and configuration options, such as:  - Baseband block configuration  - Cell technology  - Carrier Bandwidth  - PUCCH mode (long PUCCH, short PUCCH)  - PRB blanking  - DSS  If NRBTS.actScheUePooling is equal to TRUE or NRBTS.actBbPoolTddFr1 is equal to TRUE, for FDD cells or TDD FR1 cells, the recommended value of this parameter should be greater than 1.  For FDD and TDD cells on FR1, this parameter is ignored if NRCELL.actIncreasedFdmUsersPerSlot is equal to FALSE and UE pooling is disabled (NRBTS.actScheUePooling is equal to FALSE or NRBTS.actBbPoolTddFr1 is equal to FALSE).

Parameter name: Maximum number of secondary cells for FR1 DL CA
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of FR1 secondary cells (SCells) a gNB can configure in the 5G UE for DL carrier aggregation in addition to the primary cell (PCell).  It is only applied to 4CC and above CA.

Parameter name: Maximum number of UEs in power saving bandwidth Part
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of UEs that can be accommodated in the power saving bandwidth part

Parameter name: Max number of VoNR UEs in power saving bandwidth Part
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of UEs with at least one VoNR bearer that can be accommodated in the power saving bandwidth part

Parameter name: Maximum NBR DRB PRBs per UE
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of PRBs allocated for NBR traffic per UE in uplink and downlink.  The amount of radio resources (PRBs) is computed in % of the available PRBs depending on the system.

Parameter name: Max. number of PRBs used for increased coding gain for VoNR UEs
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of PRBs including added PRBs in the process of incrementing the PRBs to harness the coding gain for the VoNR UEs (with 5Q1 bearer(s))
Mobile Country Code of the gNB. Parameter used and visible only in NetAct Advanced Configurator.
This parameter defines the MCS index used in the artificial PDSCH load.    Note: 256QAM is not supported for the artificial load, Table 5.1.3.1-1 defined in 3GPP 38.214 is always used.
This parameter indicates the measurement gap pattern selection criteria to be used by gNB during selection of measurement gap pattern in NSA mode.
This parameter indicates the measurement gap pattern selection criteria to be used by gNB during selection of measurement gap pattern in SA mode.

Parameter name: Measurement profile mapping list for NSA
Description: This structure contains a list of measurement profile mapping parameters for NSA.
This parameter indicates the measurement profile priority of the New Radio Measurement Profile Mapping NSA.  Value 1 means the highest priority, while value 100 means the lowest priority.

This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated NRMEASPR_MA_NSA instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRMEAS_PROFILE-1/NRMEASPR_MA_NSA-1  NRMEASPR_MA_NSA-1

Parameter name: Measurement profile mapping list for SA
Description: This structure contains a list of measurement profile mapping parameters for SA.
This parameter indicates the measurement profile priority of the New Radio Measurement Profile Mapping SA.  Value 1 means the highest priority, while value 100 means the lowest priority.

This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated NRMEASPR_MA_SA instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRMEAS_PROFILE-1/NRMEASPR_MA_SA-1  NRMEASPR_MA_SA-1
This parameter indicates the measurement gap timing advance in ms

Parameter name: Minimum percentage of resources for reserved MCS DL
Description: This parameter indicates the minimum amount of physical channel bits in percentage requested for an adaptive retransmission based on reserved MCS on PDSCH with reference to the physical channel bits allocated by the initial transmission.  If it is set to 100 the same amount of physical channel bits is used for the retransmission as allocated by the initial transmission.

Parameter name: Minimum percentage of resources for reserved MCS UL
Description: This parameter indicates the minimum amount of physical channel bits in percentage requested for an adaptive retransmission based on reserved MCS on PUSCH with reference to the physical channel bits allocated by the initial transmission.  If it is set to 100 the same amount of physical channel bits is used for the retransmission as allocated by the initial transmission.

Parameter name: Minimum RBs reserved for non SI or paging messages
Description: This parameter indicates the minimum RBs reserved for non SIB/OSI/paging messages in SI/Paging slot for example msg2/4. These RBs are not assigned for SIB/OSI/paging messages.  It shall not exceed the following maximum value, based on the size of CORESET(0):  - If this size is equal to 24, then this maximum value is 17  - If this size is equal to 48, then this maximum value is 34  - If this size is equal to 96, then this maximum value is 68

Parameter name: Minimum RSRP of replacement cell for PS-Cell selection
Description: This parameter indicates the minimum RSRP value to be met by the FR1 replacement cell for PS-Cell selection (during NSA initial access).  It is used by the gNB only when this cell (i.e. the current NRCELL instance) is defined as replacement cell via the NRREL instance(s) of any other FR1 cell.  If this parameter is not configured, then the RSRP value of the FR1 replacement cell will not be checked. The actual value is (NRCELL.minRsrpRplCellForPSCell - 157) dBm, except for the special value 127, in which case the actual value is infinity.

Parameter name: Minimum RSRQ of replacement cell For PS-Cell selection
Description: This parameter indicates the minimum RSRQ value to be met by the FR1 replacement cell for PS-Cell selection (during NSA initial access).  It is used by the gNB only when this cell (i.e. the current NRCELL instance) is defined as replacement cell via the NRREL instance(s) of any other FR1 cell.  If this parameter is not configured, then the RSRQ value of the FR1 replacement cell will not be checked. The actual value is (NRCELL.minRsrqRplCellForPSCell- 87) / 2 dB.

Parameter name: Minimum TBS size for uplink PUSCH slot aggregation
Description: This parameter indicates the 5QI1 VoNR specific minimum TBS size when PUSCH slot aggregation is used.  This is the expected TBS size for one VoNR packet assuming RoHC header compression, the use of no segmentation and including some allowance for PHRs and BSRs. Nominal values for a 13.2 Kbps or a 12.6 Kbps Vocoder is 384 bits. Nominal value for a 23.8 Kbps Vocoder is 552 bits.

Parameter name: Cell level Parameter set for AI/ML based CA use case
Description: This parameter contains all cell level parameters for AI/ML based 5G secondary cell activation use case
This parameter defines the operational state of ML inference for CA secondary cell activation use case.
Mobile Network Code of the gNB. Parameter used and visible only in NetAct Advanced Configurator.
Length of Mobile Network Code. Parameter used and visible only in NetAct Advanced Configurator.

Parameter name: List of BBMOD or SMOD distinguished names
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the BBMOD or SMOD instance(s) representing the module(s) where the L1 part of the NRCELL is mapped.  Note: a NRCELL can be mapped on more than 1 BBMOD.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/EQM-1/APEQM-50/CABINET-1/BBMOD-1.  MRBTS-1/EQM-1/APEQM-1/CABINET-1/SMOD-1
This parameter defines the length of the modification period.  Modification period = NRCELL.modPeriodCoeff * NRBTS.drxDefaultPaging.  Modification period is equal or lower than 1024.

This parameter defines the PRACH Frequency start. It corresponds to RRC parameter 'msg1-FrequencyStart' (see 38.331) and L1 parameter 'prach-frequency-start' (see 38.211).    If NRCELL.cellDepType is equal to 'NSA', 'NR-DC-SN' or 'NR-DC-SN+NSA', it defines the offset of the lowest PRACH transmission occasion in frequency domain with respect to the PRB 0 of the configured dedicated BWP for RACH.  If NRCELL.cellDepType is equal to 'SA' or 'SA+NSA', it defines the offset of the lowest PRACH transmission occasion in frequency domain with respect to the PRB 0 of the configured initial BWP for RACH.    Setting of this parameter needs to follow the Configuration Guide for PDCCH parameters.    Note 1: The PRACH Frequency resources shall not overlap with PUCCH. For SA or SA+NSA deployment, the PRACH shall be located in the initial BWP.  Note 2: Configuration of this parameter needs follow the Configuration Guide for PDCCH and the checks inside 'Description of Parameter Relationships' can be further restricted by this guide.

This parameter indicates the alpha value used for Msg 3 transmission by the UE.  Alpha defines the possible values of the pathloss compensation coefficient for uplink power control. al0 corresponds to 0, al04 corresponds to value 0.4, al05 to 0.5, al06 to 0.6, al07 to 0.7, al08 to 0.8, al09 to 0.9 and al1 corresponds to 1
This parameter defines the power offset between msg3 and RACH preamble transmission in steps of 1dB

Parameter name: Mute last symbol in SSB slot
Description: This parameter enables/disables muting of the last symbol in SSB slot(s).  The possible values are as follows:  - 'NoMutingOfDlSymbol' meaning no muting of the last DL symbol in the SSB slots.  - 'MutingOfLastDlSymbolInSsbSlotZero' meaning muting of the last DL symbol only in SSB slot 0 (first SSB slot), when no CSI-RS is allocated in the last symbol of the 0th SSB slot.  - 'MutingOfLastDlSymbolInAllSsbSlots' meaning muting of the last DL symbol in all SSB slots, when no CSI-RS is allocated in the last symbol of the SSB slot.
This parameter indicates the maximum number of consecutive 'out of sync' indications received from lower layers.
This parameter indicates the maximum number of consecutive 'out of sync' indications received from lower layers for Voice over NR.
This parameter indicates the maximum number of consecutive 'in-sync' indications received from lower layers.
This structure gathers the data set of NG RAN access point position in the global coordinate system (GCS).
This parameter indicates the altitude value (N).
This parameter indicates the confidence by which the position of a target entity is known to be within the shape description.
This parameter indicates the latitude value (N) which is derived from the latitude in degrees with formula: N <= 2^23 X /90 < N+1, where X is the latitude in degrees (0 to 90 degrees).
This parameter indicates the longitude value (N) which is derived from the longitude in degrees with formula: N <= 2^24 X /360 < N+1, where X is the longitude in degrees (-180 to +180 degrees).
This parameter defines the direction of altitude.
This parameter indicates the latitude sign as northward or southward.
This parameter indicates the orientation of the major axis.
This parameter indicates the value of the uncertainty altitude ("uncertainty code" k).
This parameter indicates the value of the semi-major uncertainty ("uncertainty code" k)
This parameter indicates the value of the semi-minor uncertainty ("uncertainty code" k)

Parameter name: Number of UE connected for CCE split deactivation
Description: This parameter indicates the number of UE connected contexts for CCE split deactivation.
The name of the managed object.

Parameter name: Number of blanked PRBs in high edge of downlink side
Description: This parameter indicates the number of blanked PRBs in high edge of downlink side

Parameter name: Number of blanked PRBs in high edge of uplink side
Description: This parameter indicates the number of blanked PRBs in high edge of uplink side

Parameter name: Number of blanked PRBs in low edge of downlink side
Description: This parameter indicates the number of blanked PRBs in low edge of downlink side

Parameter name: Number of blanked PRBs in low edge of uplink side
Description: This parameter indicates the number of blanked PRBs in low edge of uplink side

Parameter name: Number of SSBs per RACH occasion
Description: This parameter defines the number of SSBs per RACH occasion.

Parameter name: PDCCH congestion control for DL NBR traffic
Description: This parameter enables/disables PDCCH congestion control for the downlink NBR traffic.    It is highly recommended to set it to TRUE if nominal bitrate for non-GBR bearers is activated, i.e. if NRCELL.actNbrForNonGbrBearers is equal to TRUE.

Parameter name: PDCCH congestion control for UL NBR traffic
Description: This parameter enables/disables PDCCH congestion control for the uplink NBR traffic.    It is highly recommended to set it to TRUE if nominal bitrate for non-GBR bearers is activated, i.e. if NRCELL.actNbrForNonGbrBearers is equal to TRUE.

Parameter name: PDSCH congestion control for NBR traffic
Description: This parameter enables/disables PDSCH congestion control for NBR traffic.    It is highly recommended to set it to TRUE if nominal bitrate for non-GBR bearers is activated, i.e. if NRCELL.actNbrForNonGbrBearers is equal to TRUE.

Parameter name: PUSCH congestion control for NBR traffic
Description: This parameter enables/disables PUSCH congestion control for NBR traffic.    It is highly recommended to set it to TRUE if nominal bitrate for non-GBR bearers is activated, i.e. if NRCELL.actNbrForNonGbrBearers is equal to TRUE.

Parameter name: Non GBR New Radio Discontinuous Reception Transmission distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated NRDRX instance for non GBR DRB. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRDRX-2  NRDRX-2

This parameter identifies the New Radio cell in the network (nrbtsId + lcrId). This cell identity is unique within one PLMN and has a length of 36 bits. The leftmost 22 to 32 bits of the value correspond to the value of the NRBTS ID (parameter NRBTS.nrBtsId) and the rightmost 14 to 4 bits correspond to the value of the local cell resource ID (NRCELL.lcrId).

This parameter allows the operator to specify the number of fronthaul streams of a New Radio Cell.  This parameter is also used for identification of Supplemental downlink cell. Please note that for FDD SDL cells with nrCellType equal to '2DL0UL' or '4DL0UL' certain UL parameters are irrelevant and are ignored by the gNB.    Configuring this parameter during cell addition will not provoke gNB reset.  When NRCELL.actSupercellSingleSSB is not updated, updating this parameter will provoke gNB reset.  When NRCELL.actSupercellSingleSSB is updated, updating this parameter will provoke cell reset  Removal of this parameter during cell deletion will not provoke gNB reset.  Note: In SBTS, changing this parameter will require only a 5G RAT restart.

Parameter name: New Radio Connected Mode Profile distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated NRCONNECTMODE_PROFILE instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRCONNECTMODE_PROFILE-1  NRCONNECTMODE_PROFILE-1

Parameter name: Default New Radio Mobility Profile for NSA distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the New Radio Mobility Profile for NSA (NRMOPR_NSA) instance representing the default New Radio Mobility Profile for NSA. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRMOPR_NSA-1  NRMOPR_NSA-1

Parameter name: Default New Radio Mobility Profile for SA distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the New Radio Mobility Profile for SA (NRMOPR_SA) instance representing the default New Radio Mobility Profile for SA. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRMOPR_SA-1  NRMOPR_SA-1

Parameter name: New Radio Multiband Information Profile distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated New Radio Multiband Information Profile (NRMULTIBANDINFO_PROFILE) instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRMULTIBANDINFO_PROFILE-1  NRMULTIBANDINFO_PROFILE-1

This parameter indicates the maximum number of subsequent SCG Failures without RLF recovery, i.e. subsequent SCG Failure indications, each occurring before nominal time-lag after preceding SCG Failure indication. Beyond that SgNB Release shall be triggered

Parameter name: New Radio Resource Group Profile distinguished name in DL
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated NRRESOURCEGROUP_PROFILE instance in downlink. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRRESOURCEGROUP_PROFILE-1  NRRESOURCEGROUP_PROFILE-1

Parameter name: New Radio Resource Group Profile distinguished name for RAC
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated NRRESOURCEGROUP_PROFILE instance for radio admission control. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRRESOURCEGROUP_PROFILE-1  NRRESOURCEGROUP_PROFILE-1

Parameter name: New Radio Resource Group Profile distinguished name in UL
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated NRRESOURCEGROUP_PROFILE instance in uplink. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRRESOURCEGROUP_PROFILE-1  NRRESOURCEGROUP_PROFILE-1

Parameter name: New Radio System Information NSA Profile distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the NRSYSINFO_PROFILE_NSA instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRSYSINFO_PROFILE_NSA-1  NRSYSINFO_PROFILE_NSA-1    Updating this parameter without changing the referenced instance will be performed on-line.

Parameter name: New Radio System Information Profile distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the NRSYSINFO_PROFILE instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRSYSINFO_PROFILE-1  NRSYSINFO_PROFILE-1    Updating this parameter without changing the referenced instance will be performed on-line.

Parameter name: New Radio Automatic Unified Access Control Profile distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated New Radio Automatic Unified Access Control Profile instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRUAC_AUTO_PROFILE-1  NRUAC_AUTO_PROFILE-1

Parameter name: New Radio UpLink Closed Loop Power Control Profile distinguished name
Description: This parameter indicates the distinguished name of the associated New Radio UpLink Closed Loop Power Control Profile (NRULCLPC_PROFILE) instance. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRULCLPC_PROFILE-1  NRULCLPC_PROFILE-1

Parameter name: NR Absolute radio frequency channel number
Description: New Radio Absolute Radio Frequency Channel Number.  The possible 5G NR Bands are specified in table 5.2-1/5.2-2 and the corresponding 5G NR ARFCNs in Table 5.4.2.3-1 and 5.4.2.3.-2 of 3GPP TS 38.104.  This parameter defines ARFCN for TDD bands only.  Note: The frequency range supported by a particular Radio Unit shall be checked in the latest Customer Documentation file: 'Nokia AirScale Radio Units Description'.    This parameter affects real center frequency and channel bandwidth which is not validated against radio module capabilities and misconfiguration can cause cell setup failures with fault '1900: RF Module configuring failed' raised.    Configuring this parameter during cell addition might provoke gNB reset - gNB takes decision of reset necessity.  Updating this parameter will provoke gNB reset.  Removal of this parameter during cell deletion will not provoke gNB reset.  Note: In SBTS, changing this parameter will require only a 5G RAT restart.

This parameter indicates the list of distinguished names of the NRHOIR instances (IRAT handover parameters) associated with the NR Cell. This distinguished name can be either a Fully Distinguished Name (FDN) or a shortened one as long as it is unambiguous within the network element configuration.  Examples:  MRBTS-1/NRBTS-1/NRHOIR-1  NRHOIR-1

Parameter name: Number Of Measurement Ssb To Average
Description: This parameter indicates the maximum number of measurement results per beam based on SS/PBCH blocks to be averaged. The same value applies for each detected cell in that carrier frequency.
This parameter defines the maximum number of DL HARQ processes.

Parameter name: Number of leftmost DFT beams muted
Description: This parameter indicates the number of leftmost DFT beams in horizontal which are muted. The number of beams muted is relative to the full DFT beam set. Value 0 means the full DFT beam set in left side is in use. The full DFT beam set is wider than the configured sector via NRCELL.beamSet.leftEdgeAngle/NRCELL.beamSet.rightEdgeAngle and can cause increased interference. Value 1 means 1 beam relative to the full DFT beam set in left side is muted. And so on...    If this parameter is not configured, then the DFT beams in left side are internally determined by the gNB according to the open angle setting.
